1
00:00:01,109 --> 00:00:06,109
http://hiqve.com/

2
00:00:08,133 --> 00:00:09,926
I told you I'm fine.

3
00:00:10,010 --> 00:00:11,678
I feel much stronger today

4
00:00:11,762 --> 00:00:15,431
and I'd feel much better still
if I were at home surrounded by my things.

5
00:00:15,516 --> 00:00:17,725
Well, I'd feel better
if I could keep watch on you.

6
00:00:17,810 --> 00:00:18,810
Hmm.

7
00:00:18,894 --> 00:00:22,814
There could be some latent symptoms
caused by the malaria.

8
00:00:22,898 --> 00:00:25,108
You know, fever, chills.

9
00:00:26,318 --> 00:00:29,654
Take a pinch of this
at the first sign of any symptoms.

10
00:00:29,738 --> 00:00:31,698
- It's Quinine.
- Oh.

11
00:00:32,116 --> 00:00:34,367
Now all I need do
is lay in a stock of gin and limes

12
00:00:34,451 --> 00:00:36,035
and I can make a party of it.

13
00:00:44,837 --> 00:00:47,088
Worry about your other patients, John.

14
00:00:47,172 --> 00:00:49,257
I'll look in on you later.

15
00:01:11,196 --> 00:01:12,363
One second.

16
00:01:20,998 --> 00:01:22,165
Yes?

17
00:01:55,032 --> 00:01:59,035
In the last century,
neurologists have revolutionized

18
00:01:59,369 --> 00:02:02,622
our understanding of the human brain.

19
00:02:03,040 --> 00:02:05,625
Using electric currents, they discovered

20
00:02:05,709 --> 00:02:10,797
that precise points of the brain can be
stimulated to reveal their specific functions.

21
00:02:12,424 --> 00:02:15,384
Seated in front of you is Mr. Sidney Carton.

22
00:02:15,844 --> 00:02:18,137
Mr. Carton was recently
involved in an accident

23
00:02:18,222 --> 00:02:21,390
that resulted in the loss
of the top of his cranium.

24
00:02:21,809 --> 00:02:26,854
Fortunately, for the benefit of
our experiments today,

25
00:02:26,939 --> 00:02:30,107
his brain was left unharmed.

26
00:02:41,328 --> 00:02:45,581
I will now deliver small currents
into the patient's brain to demonstrate.

27
00:02:46,875 --> 00:02:51,337
We only have a vague idea
of what happens in any given area.

28
00:02:51,421 --> 00:02:56,759
As you know, the brain itself feels no pain,
so Mr. Carton won't feel a thing.

29
00:03:19,116 --> 00:03:23,119
Electricity can also affect our emotions.

30
00:03:24,746 --> 00:03:26,622
I will now demonstrate.

31
00:03:50,147 --> 00:03:52,940
Stop. Stop.

32
00:03:53,025 --> 00:03:55,151
Stop it.

33
00:03:57,404 --> 00:03:59,196
And what about desire?

34
00:04:01,366 --> 00:04:03,951
Mr. Carton is a morphine addict.

35
00:04:04,036 --> 00:04:06,329
He injects himself multiple times a day.

36
00:04:06,955 --> 00:04:10,833
But for the past 24 hours,
he has been denied the drug.

37
00:04:21,345 --> 00:04:24,180
As you can see,
his need for the morphine is immense.

38
00:04:47,871 --> 00:04:50,331
Other than discharging electricity,

39
00:04:50,415 --> 00:04:53,501
this device, a rheoscope, can detect it.

40
00:04:56,296 --> 00:04:58,506
Using it,

41
00:04:58,590 --> 00:05:02,134
I hope to identify
the region of Mr. Carton's brain

42
00:05:02,219 --> 00:05:04,804
that is stimulated by the morphine.

43
00:05:47,180 --> 00:05:48,556
Gentlemen,

44
00:05:50,934 --> 00:05:53,686
it seems that X marks the spot.

45
00:06:31,683 --> 00:06:33,225
What's the matter with you?

46
00:06:33,310 --> 00:06:34,643
I...

47
00:06:34,728 --> 00:06:36,562
I don't know.

48
00:06:36,646 --> 00:06:38,022
Have you eaten anything today?

49
00:06:38,106 --> 00:06:40,566
It's her time of the month.

50
00:06:40,650 --> 00:06:42,234
Cramps?

51
00:06:42,319 --> 00:06:44,361
You having your monthly?

52
00:06:44,446 --> 00:06:46,447
How old are you?

53
00:06:46,531 --> 00:06:48,240
Eighteen.

54
00:06:48,325 --> 00:06:51,786
Nobody's properly taught you
about the functions of your body?

55
00:06:53,038 --> 00:06:54,622
All right.

56
00:06:54,706 --> 00:06:56,832
I'll tell you what you're going to do.

57
00:06:56,917 --> 00:07:01,420
You beg 20 cents off one of the nuns,
walk if you can to the pharmacy.

58
00:07:01,505 --> 00:07:05,091
Ask the man there
to sell you a bottle of cannabis indica.

59
00:07:05,175 --> 00:07:06,884
Cannabis indica.

60
00:07:06,968 --> 00:07:08,803
I'll write it down for you so you remember.

61
00:07:08,887 --> 00:07:12,348
Why not some hashish, too, while she's at it?

62
00:07:13,350 --> 00:07:16,185
Are you fit enough to continue with work?

63
00:07:18,021 --> 00:07:19,230
Yes, Sister.

64
00:07:20,649 --> 00:07:24,568
At the very least, give the poor girl leave
to fetch a couple of aspirin.

65
00:07:24,903 --> 00:07:29,031
Aspirin will not cure God's will.
It's the curse of Eve.

66
00:07:29,282 --> 00:07:31,951
The curse of Eve
is to bring forth children in pain,

67
00:07:32,035 --> 00:07:34,161
not to suffer menstrual cramps.

68
00:07:34,246 --> 00:07:35,746
Much the same thing.

69
00:07:36,623 --> 00:07:40,543
And I'll thank the likes of you
not to instruct me in matters of theology.

70
00:07:40,919 --> 00:07:43,129
I was just trying to help the poor girl.

71
00:07:43,213 --> 00:07:45,881
Like you helped all those unborn babies?

72
00:07:47,008 --> 00:07:50,302
Don't let me catch you
talking to these girls again, Dolan.

73
00:07:51,388 --> 00:07:54,515
Did you hear me, all the rest of you?

74
00:07:54,599 --> 00:07:57,810
This woman is the worst kind of sinner,

75
00:07:57,894 --> 00:07:59,687
an infanticide.

76
00:07:59,771 --> 00:08:01,772
And you will not speak to her.

77
00:08:01,857 --> 00:08:04,358
Not so much as a good morning.

78
00:08:04,442 --> 00:08:06,944
Unless you don't want to eat.

79
00:08:25,422 --> 00:08:27,423
Henry, this is inspired.

80
00:08:27,507 --> 00:08:30,092
Imagine the fortune you'd make
showing this on the Bowery.

81
00:08:30,886 --> 00:08:34,680
You've single-handedly
brought self-abuse into the 20th century.

82
00:08:35,098 --> 00:08:36,223
Pun intended.

83
00:08:37,058 --> 00:08:40,019
What I don't understand
is why you didn't jump in there yourself.

84
00:08:40,103 --> 00:08:43,439
Well, somebody had to crank the camera.

85
00:08:45,567 --> 00:08:46,942
I volunteer.

86
00:09:42,290 --> 00:09:44,416
What'll it be, sir?

87
00:09:44,501 --> 00:09:46,835
Care for a White Lion?

88
00:09:47,671 --> 00:09:51,757
Or perhaps a White Tiger's Milk.

89
00:09:51,841 --> 00:09:53,968
Just a couple of whiskeys.

90
00:09:54,469 --> 00:09:55,469
Hmm.

91
00:09:59,891 --> 00:10:04,144
I'm sorry, Bertie.
I couldn't think of anywhere else to take you.

92
00:10:04,229 --> 00:10:07,106
No, no. It's a novelty.

93
00:10:07,190 --> 00:10:09,525
My father will be scandalized.

94
00:10:20,370 --> 00:10:23,580
So, what is it
that you wanted to talk to me about?

95
00:10:25,667 --> 00:10:27,710
I've had some bad news.

96
00:10:27,794 --> 00:10:30,129
My mother has laryngeal cancer.

97
00:10:32,882 --> 00:10:34,800
- I'm sorry, Bertie.
- Thank you.

98
00:10:34,884 --> 00:10:36,385
That's terrible.

99
00:10:38,888 --> 00:10:40,681
What course are you considering?

100
00:10:42,392 --> 00:10:45,477
I thought perhaps
that you might have encountered

101
00:10:45,562 --> 00:10:49,898
more pioneering procedures
during your years abroad.

102
00:10:51,067 --> 00:10:53,319
Have you consulted
with Dr. Zinberg about this?

103
00:10:53,403 --> 00:10:57,489
No, Dr. Zinberg is the kind of man
who wears both suspenders and a belt,

104
00:10:57,574 --> 00:10:59,241
if you take my meaning.

105
00:10:59,326 --> 00:11:00,701
He would never approve a procedure

106
00:11:00,785 --> 00:11:05,247
that hadn't passed years of rigorous
laboratory experimentation and peer review.

107
00:11:06,750 --> 00:11:09,335
I have to say I feel like
it's because he's a Jew.

108
00:11:10,128 --> 00:11:12,254
I believe being a universally despised race

109
00:11:12,339 --> 00:11:14,173
has stiffened their resolve
to never act rashly

110
00:11:14,257 --> 00:11:17,426
and risk being thought a failure
in the eyes of a hostile world.

111
00:11:21,473 --> 00:11:24,850
Some months ago,
I read a paper coauthored by Pierre Curie

112
00:11:24,934 --> 00:11:29,772
on the treatment of malignant tumors using
radium and other radioactive substances.

113
00:11:31,024 --> 00:11:35,277
I could translate it from the French
if you could find a copy of it somewhere.

114
00:11:36,988 --> 00:11:40,074
Bertie,
you smell just like McSorley's Bar.

115
00:11:40,158 --> 00:11:41,950
Have you been in a saloon tonight?

116
00:11:42,035 --> 00:11:44,453
How do you know
what McSorley's smells like, huh?

117
00:11:44,662 --> 00:11:47,081
I didn't think they permitted women in there.

118
00:11:47,248 --> 00:11:49,083
I have ways
of getting into places.

119
00:11:52,670 --> 00:11:54,838
Bertie, how on earth did you do this?

120
00:11:55,507 --> 00:11:57,966
Well, I, too, have ways
of getting into places.

121
00:12:01,137 --> 00:12:02,805
You find anything?

122
00:12:02,889 --> 00:12:06,642
No, but you're still researching adrenaline,
aren't you?

123
00:12:07,060 --> 00:12:08,519
Yes. Why?

124
00:12:09,187 --> 00:12:12,648
Because here's a paper about it
from the University of Kraków.

125
00:12:15,777 --> 00:12:16,860
You read Polish?

126
00:12:17,946 --> 00:12:19,029
Yeah.

127
00:12:20,115 --> 00:12:21,407
Very impressive.

128
00:12:21,491 --> 00:12:23,075
Voilà.

129
00:12:23,159 --> 00:12:26,203
The French Academy of Sciences,
December 1900.

130
00:12:29,416 --> 00:12:30,791
This is it.

131
00:12:30,875 --> 00:12:33,710
So how often do you engage
in criminal activity?

132
00:12:34,504 --> 00:12:36,171
Not often.

133
00:12:36,256 --> 00:12:37,965
Please don't tell my mother.

134
00:12:38,049 --> 00:12:40,134
If she found out
that I'd become a second-story man,

135
00:12:40,218 --> 00:12:41,760
she'd be heartbroken.

136
00:13:00,989 --> 00:13:02,531
Henry Robertson.

137
00:13:03,867 --> 00:13:05,200
What?

138
00:13:11,124 --> 00:13:12,708
Yeah, let me call you back.

139
00:13:28,224 --> 00:13:29,600
I'll go in the back.

140
00:13:37,442 --> 00:13:39,610
- What happened?
- Dynamite explosion.

141
00:13:39,694 --> 00:13:41,820
Subway excavation on Park Avenue.

142
00:13:41,905 --> 00:13:43,113
- How many injured?
- Don't know.

143
00:13:43,198 --> 00:13:45,115
They're still pulling
bodies out of the ground.

144
00:13:45,200 --> 00:13:47,576
But it's not gonna end any time soon.

145
00:13:48,119 --> 00:13:49,369
Thack, where should we put them?

146
00:13:49,454 --> 00:13:51,955
- The wards?
- No, we'll need them for recovery.

147
00:13:52,040 --> 00:13:55,751
Fetch every operating table in the hospital
and get them into the theater.

148
00:13:55,835 --> 00:13:58,086
- Help him, Edwards.
- No, I should stay and sort the patients.

149
00:13:58,171 --> 00:14:01,173
No, Nurse Elkins is more than qualified.

150
00:14:01,257 --> 00:14:02,216
Any questions?

151
00:14:02,300 --> 00:14:04,384
- Should I use the hallways as a waiting room?
- Good.

152
00:14:04,469 --> 00:14:07,262
Anything else,
just make it up as you go along.

153
00:14:10,141 --> 00:14:11,517
Yeah, up front. You're driving.

154
00:14:11,601 --> 00:14:13,644
You're gonna let me drive?

155
00:14:14,979 --> 00:14:16,188
I'm staying here.

156
00:14:16,272 --> 00:14:18,524
Someone's got to ride roughshod
over the likes of them.

157
00:14:18,608 --> 00:14:22,152
Ambulances coming in from all over.
Whoa, whoa, whoa.

158
00:14:22,779 --> 00:14:23,862
Get the fuck out of here, man.

159
00:14:23,947 --> 00:14:25,739
How in the hell do you drive this thing?

160
00:14:28,159 --> 00:14:30,702
- So what do we have?
- His pelvis is shattered.

161
00:14:30,787 --> 00:14:33,705
Need to resect the gut
and set the bone somehow.

162
00:14:33,790 --> 00:14:37,209
There's no time. Splint the hips,
staunch the bleeds, and shove the rest inside.

163
00:14:37,293 --> 00:14:41,046
- I don't need your advice, Edwards.
- He's right, Everett. Just do what he says.

164
00:14:43,383 --> 00:14:44,883
How deeply embedded do you think this is?

165
00:14:44,968 --> 00:14:46,760
Hopefully not as far as the lungs.

166
00:14:46,844 --> 00:14:51,223
I don't see any external trauma,
but stand by just in case.

167
00:15:03,820 --> 00:15:05,529
Lung's collapsed.

168
00:15:05,613 --> 00:15:07,322
- Scalpel.
- Bring him in.

169
00:15:12,161 --> 00:15:13,495
Trocar.

170
00:15:26,009 --> 00:15:27,217
Dr. Thackery.

171
00:15:29,178 --> 00:15:30,637
- You got it?
- Dr. Thackery.

172
00:15:34,225 --> 00:15:37,311
Okay, let's clean him up,
see how deep they are.

173
00:15:39,230 --> 00:15:40,689
Coming in, right now.

174
00:15:47,989 --> 00:15:50,365
Don't. Don't pull it out
or you'll bleed to death.

175
00:15:50,450 --> 00:15:52,284
We're gonna get you right into surgery.

176
00:15:53,911 --> 00:15:55,454
Ten grains of morphine.

177
00:15:56,873 --> 00:15:59,041
That compound fracture can wait.

178
00:16:00,835 --> 00:16:02,878
Let's get some pressure under his head.

179
00:16:06,924 --> 00:16:09,968
Nurse Beckman? This is Henry Robertson.

180
00:16:10,053 --> 00:16:13,972
Hello. Look, we have an emergency.
We need all nurses here immediately.

181
00:16:14,057 --> 00:16:16,391
You live with Nurse Nash, don't you?

182
00:16:16,517 --> 00:16:18,018
No need to get changed.

183
00:16:18,102 --> 00:16:21,396
Report directly to Nurse Taylor.
She'll tell you where you're most needed.

184
00:16:21,481 --> 00:16:24,358
And don't bother with
normal admissions protocol.

185
00:16:24,442 --> 00:16:28,236
Just sign them all in as John Doe
and we'll sort it out later.

186
00:16:29,364 --> 00:16:32,699
Nurse Taylor, I have
four more sets of hands for you.

187
00:16:33,576 --> 00:16:34,868
Orderly.

188
00:16:35,370 --> 00:16:37,162
We're out of beds and gurneys.

189
00:16:37,246 --> 00:16:42,084
I need you to find every couch, bench, chair,
anything you can lay a patient on.

190
00:16:42,168 --> 00:16:43,669
No room is off-limits.

191
00:16:50,677 --> 00:16:52,177
Where the fuck do you think you're going?

192
00:16:52,261 --> 00:16:54,888
Out of my way, Cleary.
I need to see a man about my carting fees.

193
00:16:54,972 --> 00:16:56,682
- How many?
- That was the fourth.

194
00:16:56,766 --> 00:16:58,809
And they were all still breathing
when I got here.

195
00:16:58,893 --> 00:17:01,520
Your hospital administrator owes me
a total of four simoleons.

196
00:17:01,604 --> 00:17:03,772
- Now, will you kindly let me pass?
- No.

197
00:17:03,856 --> 00:17:05,691
But I'll tell you what I will do.

198
00:17:05,775 --> 00:17:07,359
I'll take your name down and I'll make sure

199
00:17:07,443 --> 00:17:09,861
that Mr. Barrow's aware of
the Knick's debt to you.

200
00:17:09,946 --> 00:17:13,115
I'm sure he'll get around to paying it
in three weeks or so.

201
00:17:13,199 --> 00:17:14,950
Three weeks?

202
00:17:15,034 --> 00:17:18,870
Or you can have your money
right now from me.

203
00:17:18,955 --> 00:17:20,539
What's the catch?

204
00:17:20,623 --> 00:17:24,334
The catch is I'm offering two bits per.

205
00:17:24,419 --> 00:17:26,253
Two bits per body.

206
00:17:26,337 --> 00:17:28,588
So instead of waiting three weeks
for the $4 I'm owed,

207
00:17:28,673 --> 00:17:31,216
you're offering to pay me $1 right now?

208
00:17:31,300 --> 00:17:33,260
Cash on the barrelhead.

209
00:17:42,478 --> 00:17:43,520
Excuse me.

210
00:17:43,938 --> 00:17:46,732
Help me. Help me. You've got to help me.

211
00:17:47,942 --> 00:17:50,527
- Take him straight to surgery.
- But I...

212
00:17:50,611 --> 00:17:53,029
I have a wife and a little daughter.

213
00:17:54,365 --> 00:17:56,116
Dr. Thackery.

214
00:17:58,202 --> 00:18:00,245
Finish up and dress the wound.

215
00:18:00,329 --> 00:18:01,663
Yes, Doctor.

216
00:18:14,343 --> 00:18:16,928
Put him under.

217
00:18:17,847 --> 00:18:20,432
I can't go slicing around.
He's losing too much blood.

218
00:18:20,516 --> 00:18:23,268
- The X-ray is full.
- No time for that.

219
00:18:43,164 --> 00:18:44,790
What are you doing?

220
00:18:44,874 --> 00:18:47,209
I'm gonna use this wire as a probe.

221
00:18:48,461 --> 00:18:51,379
If it comes in contact with any metal,

222
00:18:51,464 --> 00:18:54,049
then it'll close the circuit

223
00:18:55,051 --> 00:18:57,219
and we should be able to hear it.

224
00:19:01,432 --> 00:19:03,308
Come with me.

225
00:19:03,392 --> 00:19:04,768
Towel clamp.

226
00:19:28,376 --> 00:19:29,584
I hear something.

227
00:19:30,086 --> 00:19:32,128
- A crackle.
- Forceps.

228
00:19:54,318 --> 00:19:57,362
Ambulances have begun arriving less often.

229
00:19:57,446 --> 00:19:58,530
Good.

230
00:19:58,614 --> 00:20:02,284
I had a look around the wards
and they're full to bursting.

231
00:20:02,368 --> 00:20:04,411
Just what I wanted to talk with you about.

232
00:20:04,495 --> 00:20:06,705
Have you any thoughts as to
how much we should charge

233
00:20:06,789 --> 00:20:08,623
the subway construction company?

234
00:20:11,669 --> 00:20:13,211
Charge them nothing.

235
00:20:14,839 --> 00:20:16,631
Beg your pardon?

236
00:20:16,716 --> 00:20:21,052
This is nothing less than a civic duty.
We won't take a penny for it.

237
00:20:21,137 --> 00:20:22,804
It would be dishonorable.

238
00:20:24,181 --> 00:20:26,725
Nobody makes a profit here today.

239
00:20:50,833 --> 00:20:52,167
Quite a day.

240
00:20:53,169 --> 00:20:56,212
I, for one, am glad to see it end.

241
00:20:57,465 --> 00:21:01,384
And now we come
to the hour of our settlement.

242
00:21:01,469 --> 00:21:04,930
That's 124 patients in total.

243
00:21:05,014 --> 00:21:07,641
A new milestone for the Knick.

244
00:21:07,725 --> 00:21:10,810
And myself, personally, I don't mind saying.

245
00:21:10,895 --> 00:21:13,313
Cleary, you can't honestly
expect me to believe

246
00:21:13,397 --> 00:21:16,900
you carted 124 patients here by yourself.

247
00:21:18,444 --> 00:21:22,197
Let's just say I made a little arrangement
with the other fellas.

248
00:21:22,782 --> 00:21:24,532
How much did you pay them?

249
00:21:24,617 --> 00:21:26,284
Two bits a head.

250
00:21:27,161 --> 00:21:29,287
Not a bad return.

251
00:21:29,372 --> 00:21:33,833
$124 from a $31 investment.

252
00:21:35,378 --> 00:21:40,256
Unfortunately, I think you'll find
you squandered your capital.

253
